E13.E13_01: Dispatched to the priority 1 response to 92 Charwood Circle for the patient with the AICD activation. Responded immediately. Arrived to find female patient supine on couch, pale in color, complaining of feeling like she is going to pass out. She relates that approximately one hour ago her implanted defibrillator fired once. She relates that she had the pacemaker/defibrillator put in this past November, but she reports that she has been having some "issues" with the settings of the device. She further reports that despite the pacemaker being in, she is regularly in A-Fib and the doctor can not figure out why. She relates that shortly after her AICD fired she laid on the floor and thinks she may have passed out. She also relates that she had chest pain earlier today, but does not currently. She denies headache, shortness of breath, chest pain, chest pressure, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, dizziness, fever, chills, cough, or any other complaints. Arrived at patient. Introductions made. Report obtained from patient and FD, who report that they are unable to obtain a BP. Patient is pale in color and clammy. Patient placed on cardiac monitor. Vital signs obtained. Patient is assisted to sitting position and vital signs are obtained, without change. Patient is assisted to stand and pivot to stair chair. Secured via seat belt and moved to stretcher. Stair chair placed on stretcher and patient is secured with head elevated 45 degrees. Secured with seat belts. En route to SMH. Patient denies any change in complaints. Bg obtained via IV catheter. Patient denies any change in complaints, but relates that she is scared. She reports that she feels as though something is really wrong. Patient relates that she is feeling a little better. She denies any complaints at this time. No change in patient status. Arrived at SMH. Moved into ED via stretcher. To hallway bed while awaiting room assignment via scoot over. Side rails up. Bed in low position. Care and report to ED RN. Patient signed NPP form.

E09.E09_05: Pt complained of abnormal weakness in his legs.

E13.E13_01: The patient's family is on scene and explained that all morning, the patient has been having severe difficulty ambulating and that he cannot stand. The patient greeted EMS and stated that he "feels like crap". He stated that he cannot walk and hasn't really been able to stand all morning. He denied having physical pain or discomfort, and stated that his breathing felt normal. The patient continued and stated that last night he felt fine, and just woke up feeling weak. His family stated that they have noticed abnormal twitches in his arms and legs, which may be causing his legs to buckle. They stated that they have only seen twitches like that once with him, and he has been taking Dilatin since. During transport, the patient stated that he felt like he couldn't breathe but that stopped once in the ambulance. Initial patient contact and assessment. Pt is found sitting upright in the back study area of his house. Initial vital signs obtained. Pt denied feeling physical pain or discomfort. Pt was assisted to his feet to test his stability. Pt has a stable gait and is able to ambulate. He was assisted into the hallway. During movement, the patient's extremities began to buckle and twitch. No seizure-like activity noted. Pt was assisted onto a kitchen chair to sit. Vital signs obtained. No orthostatic changes noted after movement. Pt reported feeling difficulty breathing. Lung sounds auscultated with no abnormalities noted. Breathing was coached. Pt was assisted to the standing position and was secured to the track-stair chair. He was moved out of the house. Pt was assisted off the chair and on to the stretcher. Coached breathing continued. He was secured to the stretcher and moved to the ambulance. Pt was loaded into the ambulance. Pt was placed on waveform capnography to better monitor his breathing. Initial reading 18mmHg. 3 lead 12 lead Vital signs obtained. BP considered unreliable due to patient movement. Due to patient condition, sporadic movement, and proximity to the hospital, IV access was not attempted. FSBG was attempted. Due to poor blood return, one was not obtained. Vital signs obtained. BP still considered inaccurate due to patient movement. Pt at RGH triage RN. Pt was moved to hall bed P, outside of room 19, per the triage RN. He was disconnected from EMS equipment. Pt was moved into bed, via sheet slide, and was left lying in his POC in bed. Oral report of his condition was given to the attending RN.

Per pt's caregiver pt is ill and became weak, nauseated, and vomited starting around 1130hrs. she states he became progressively weaker and less responsive prompting a call to 911. She denies any trauma today, but states he has been sick for "weeks". Pt contact made, received reports from pt's caregiver. Primary and secondary assessments performed. pt moved via body lift to stairchair and from 2nd floor apartment to stretcher. pt moved via stetcher to ambulance. pt now in ambulance. No change in patient status. arrival at RGH arrival at triage pt triaged to CT scanner 64, moved to scanner bed via drawsheet report to Stroke team.
